            "answer_text": "I can\u2019t believe it, I just wrote a 5-paragraph long answer about this one battle and I accidentally deleted it all\u2026 I will cut short this time, sorry. Siege of Nagykanizsa, 1601 During the long war, the Ottoman army was getting closer to Austria. They took the Nagykanizsa castle. Then the main army left the castle leaving behind a garrison of 9,000 Jannisarys and 100 small cannons. Upon hearing that the main army left, Archduke Ferdinand II gathered his army which contained soldiers from Austria, Hungary, Spain, the Papal States and the Knights of John. 35,000\u2013100,000 men in total with the addition of 47 great cannons. They besieged the castle. The commander of the garrison, Hasan Pasha, decided to shoot back with only rifles at first, not cannons. After a while Ferdinand II thought that the Ottoman garrison had no cannons and began the main attack to the walls of the castle, but this time the Ottoman cannons open fire and the enemy army faced a massive loss. After 72 days of siege and mind games such as these, the Ottoman army had very few supplies left. On the 73rd day they advanced out of the castle and attacked the enemy\u2019s encampment at night. The Austrian Army was routed and they fled the field. Leaving behind 47 great cannons, 16,000 rifles, 60,000 tents to loot, supply enough to hold the castle for another year and, suprisingly, the golden throne of Ferdinand. Casualties on the Austrian side was very heavy. Eighty thousand according to some sources. Meanwhile the Ottomans lost hardly a 1,000 men. During and after the siege Ferdinand II was so furious he offered 40 villages to the man who brings the head of Hasan Pasha. Battle of Sirpsindigi, 1364 Or the First Battle of Maritsa River. The Turks took Edirne along with most of Thrace, so they were cutting a line between Istanbul (or Constantinople at the time) and the Balkans. In response the Balkan countries started to act and attacked the Ottoman Empire. Bosnia, Serbia and Hungary united their army along with pretty much all of the Balkans. Majority of the army were Serbs. This was the first crusade that Ottomans ever faced. Total number of the crusade army was 30,000\u201360,000. Upon hearing the crusade army was launching an attack on the Ottomans, Sultan Murad couldn\u2019t do anything. He was dealing with a rebellion in Anatolia. Only the army in Thrace, under the command of Lala Sahin Pasha could react. This army contained 11,000 or 12,000 men, mostly horse archers and Akinjiis.  Murad ordered Lala Sahin Pasha to defend the Maritsa river. But Lala Sahin Pasha realized the crusader army already passed the river and was encamping just two days away from Edirne. Pasha didn\u2019t listen the orders and attacked the encampment wildly. The Crusader army didn\u2019t know what hit them and faced a great many losses resulting in a rout with the army fleeing the field. The Ottomans chased them to the river. Most of the crusader army was drowned while trying to cross the river. Total lost of the crusader army was around 60,000 while Turks only lost 1,000. This battle created a sense of revenge for the Serbs. Which led to\u2026 Second Battle of Maritsa River Serbs, wanting to take revenge from the Ottomans, finally found a chance on the September of 1371 and they acted. They wanted to attack Edirne while Sultan Murad was at Anatolia. Doing so they would catch the Ottomans from their rear. The Serbian army had a total number of 70,000 men. The only forces left in the area to face them was just 800 men. Mostly again Akinjiis. These 800 men allowed the Serbian army to move forward until they encamp in Ormenio. At night Ottoman troops attacked the Serbian encampment. They got inside the lines quickly and the Serbian army who were caught unprepared were crushed totally after their commander was killed. Thousands of Serbian soldiers were killed and more were drowned while crossing the Maritsa river. It was told that the river turned red by the blood of dead soldiers. Losses of Ottoman troops were few. After the battle Ottomans expanded widely in Thrace and Greece. Also Serbia became the vassal of the Ottomans. There are many more but these are the most impactful ones. Specially the battles of Maritsa river. Those battles could have ended the Ottomans if they were lost. People usually think about Jannisarys when they imagine a Ottoman army. But I think these two battles proves the tactical superiority and toughness of Akinjiis. ",
